NOTICE — Third-party pattern attribution
========================================

Loom incorporates design patterns, vocabulary, and pedagogical frameworks
originally articulated by Matt Pocock in his TypeScript and developer-tooling
educational content. These patterns are adapted under the MIT License that
governs the relevant source material.

The following six patterns are attributed to Matt Pocock:

1. codebase-design vocabulary
   The Module / Interface / Seam / Adapter / Leverage / Locality / Depth
   vocabulary table (protocols/codebase-design.md) and the guidance on
   how to reason about software architecture using those terms were inspired
   by Matt Pocock's codebase-design vocabulary as described in his public
   TypeScript educational material.
   Source: mattpocock/skills (MIT License)

2. feedback-loop ladder
   The 10-rung feedback-loop ladder structure encoded in the feedback-loop
   skill (skills/feedback-loop/SKILL.md), including the TRDA gate criteria
   and the leading words "tight" and "red", was adapted from the
   feedback-loop ladder pattern in Matt Pocock's skills content.
   Source: mattpocock/skills (MIT License)

3. writing-great-skills no-op test
   The no-op test pattern described in protocols/skill-authoring.md —
   where a skill is evaluated by running it on a task it should handle,
   verifying it does not silently pass a task it cannot handle — was
   derived from the writing-great-skills no-op test framing in
   Matt Pocock's skill-authoring guidance.
   Source: mattpocock/skills (MIT License)

4. horizontal-slice anti-pattern
   The horizontal-slice anti-pattern (avoid dividing work by technical
   layer; instead cut vertically through all layers for each tracer bullet)
   adopted verbatim in the tdd-coach agent (agents/tdd-coach.md) was
   adapted from the horizontal-slice anti-pattern teaching in
   Matt Pocock's TDD framing.
   Source: mattpocock/skills (MIT License)

5. throwaway-prototype branches
   The throwaway-prototype branch discipline — create a named prototype
   branch, explore freely, write a one-line answer.toon at the completion
   ceremony, then delete the branch — was adapted from the
   throwaway-prototype branches pattern in Matt Pocock's skills content.
   Source: mattpocock/skills (MIT License)

6. grilling discipline
   The grilling discipline — structured interrogation using a capped
   question count (12 questions maximum per session), a progress indicator,
   and a /skip escape hatch — encoded in protocols/grilling.md was adapted
   from the grilling discipline pattern in Matt Pocock's skills content.
   Source: mattpocock/skills (MIT License)

